        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>David DeCasseres Esqre<lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/>
                Official duties prevented my replying to<lb/> your favor of last Saturday any earlier.  I now beg leave<lb/> to say that essentially no difference exists&#44; at present&#44; in the names<lb/> &#34;Hebrew&#34;&#45;&#45;&#34;Israelite&#34;&#45;&#45;and &#34;Jew.&#34;  In their origin&#44; however&#44; they are<lb/> distinct.  I must premise a remark.  The derivation<lb/> of <del><hi rend="underline">Eber or Heber</hi></del> <hi rend="underline">Hebrew</hi> is still an open question.  While some have claimed<lb/> that it was assured as a racial appellation from &#34;Eber&#34; or &#34;Heber&#44;&#34;<lb/> son of Shelah&#44; a lineal descendant of Noah &#40;In Genesis XI. 16&#41; <del>and</del> with<lb/> whose life Rabbinical legends are connected&#44; others have intended that<lb/> it was given in Canaan to Abraham and possibly also to others<lb/> who came to that country from Syria across the Euphrates &#40;the word<lb/> Eber&#44; meaning in the language of Canaan &#34;passage over&#34;&#41; at<lb/> all wants&#44; the patriarchs were known as <hi rend="underline">Hebrews</hi>&#44; for Moses addressed<lb/> Pharaoh in the name of &#34;the God of the Hebrews.&#34;<lb/>
                &#34;Israelite&#34; scarcely needs an explanation.  &#34;Jacob&#44;&#34; bearing <del>bering</del> an equivocal<lb/> signification &#40;see Genesis XXV.26 &#38; XXVII.36&#41; his successors preferred<lb/> that of Israel&#44; or he who struggles powerfully.  This appellation<lb/> was long retained&#44; superseding almost entirely that of &#34;Hebrew.&#34;<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
                But the schism in the days of &#91;&#63;&#93; &#40;see II Kings<lb/> XII.16&#45;19 and <del>Ch</del> 2<hi rend="sup">nd</hi> Chronicles X16&#45;19&#41; gave rise to the<lb/> name <hi rend="underline">Jehudi</hi> from Jehudah since <del>For</del> the tribe of Judah&#44;<lb/>&#45;&#45;including Benjamin&#44; too small to be separately mentioned&#8212;con<lb/>tinued faithful to the house of David and invariable <del>partly</del>&#44; at least&#44; to the<lb/> cause of monotheism&#44; while the largest portion of the other ten tribes<lb/> deserted both.  At the return from the Babylonian<lb/> exile&#44; those who accompanied &#91;&#63;&#93;abel&#44; and afterwards Ezra the<lb/> priest&#44; may have mainly belonged to Judah&#59; hence&#44; the name<lb/> &#34;Judean&#34; or one inhabiting the land called <hi rend="underline">Judea</hi> after Judah was with propriety applied to the people of the ancient<lb/> faith.  <del>For a long series of ages</del> But when vulgar prejudice<lb/> began to attach an <del>opporbas</del> &#91;&#63;&#93; signification to that name&#44; the<lb/> ill&#45;&#91;&#63;&#93; over&#44; no doubt chose &#34;Israelite&#34; instead with a view to escape results.  Now the word<lb/> <hi rend="underline">Judean</hi> came to be perverted into &#34;Jew&#34; in English&#44; and J&#91;&#63;&#93; in Spanish&#44;<lb/> I <del>cann</del> am unable to say.  <del>More are</del> Nearer to <del>the Heb</del> <hi rend="underline">Jehudi</hi><lb/> is the Spanish &#34;Judis&#44;&#34; the Italian &#34;Guidio&#44;&#34; and the German<lb/> <del>Jid</del> &#34;Jude.&#34;<lb/>
                In reality&#44; &#34;Jew&#34; as the English will have it&#8212;ought to be considered<lb/> an honorable epithet&#44; for it historically implies ad homin to the monotheistic<lb/> idea&#44; whereas <del>the</del> &#34;Israelite&#44;&#34; might recall&#44; desertion.  Still fashion is<lb/> law&#44; and few possess the moral courage to oppose it.<lb/>
                Yours truly<lb/>
                January 31<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 1882								S Morais<lb/></p>
